WEBVTT

00:01.600 --> 00:16.507
So with the innovation program, they had a thing 
called the TIG, Technology Innovation Group.

00:19.112 --> 00:22.498
And the thrust of this was to try to develop new 
technologies. And as it turned out, this focused

00:22.518 --> 00:25.684
largely on computer technology in all the cities. 
and

00:26.035 --> 00:35.683
waste

00:26.035 --> 00:35.683
disposal technologies and stuff like that. And we 
had I don't know how many cities we eventually

00:37.485 --> 00:43.170
worked with. I think it was something between 50 
and 60 cities in the state of Texas. In addition to

00:48.775 --> 00:54.760
that, we had, through the NSF program, we created a 
backup agency to help Little Rock, Arkansas, and

00:55.634 --> 01:06.092
Boulder, Colorado.

01:06.112 --> 01:09.858
So it was a tremendously successful program. And 
then in the, what, about 76, I guess it was, then we

01:09.979 --> 01:20.697
hired Don Moore, who replaced me as the director of 
the center. And of course it went on up until the

01:22.195 --> 01:36.794
early 80s, and the federal funding report 
disappeared, and things went downhill pretty

01:22.195 --> 01:36.794
rapidly. It was a separate center at that time, and 
I had nothing to do with it. And then

01:46.606 --> 01:52.033
the HUD support dried up and NSF support dried up. 
And I guess, to me, one of the saddest elements of

01:57.305 --> 02:08.736
that whole thing was that the cities wouldn't

01:57.305 --> 02:08.736
support us. And I guess I shouldn't have been too 
surprised at that, but I was.

02:15.863 --> 02:21.008
We had, over the decade of the 70s or the last half of 
it, We had developed,

02:21.815 --> 02:28.428
I thought, excellent rapport with the cities. 
They're very applied in their concerns. And you

02:34.539 --> 02:40.891
have to be careful about the words that you use in 
working with them. For example, we learned rather

02:40.911 --> 02:43.857
quickly, you don't say research. Because when you 
say research, a city councilman in Abilene or

02:44.647 --> 02:57.002
whatever will conjure up some guy in a white coat 
surrounded by test tubes. And they're not

02:57.022 --> 03:01.408
interested in funding anyone, so we called it 
property-solving. But in spite of that, and in

03:01.428 --> 03:12.882
spite of the fact that we had done, I thought, a hell 
of a lot of good things for the cities, Don Moore,

03:01.428 --> 03:12.882
and there was never a more able guy, Don Moore was

03:13.823 --> 03:27.777
just unable to draw any support from Texas cities 
to continue

03:13.823 --> 03:27.777
that. And when Dr. Porter took over TEAS, his edict 
was, if it can't be self-supporting,

03:27.798 --> 03:36.166
I'm not interested in supporting it. And I think 
it's wrong of you, frankly, but because this still

03:36.226 --> 03:41.772
is a land grant college, I think we still have duty

03:44.587 --> 04:04.327
to

03:44.587 --> 04:04.327
help

03:44.587 --> 04:04.327
the people of the state of Texas, and I think that's 
one of the things that we've done. But I went to him

04:04.347 --> 04:10.493
when the Center was essentially given, the 
program operation was essentially given back to

04:04.347 --> 04:10.493
